Definition 2.5. [14, VII.1.] Consider $A,C\in\mathcal{C}$. (1) Let $\operatorname{Ext}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}\left(C,A\right):=\mathcal{E}_{\mathcal{C}% }(C,A)/\equiv\mbox{;}$ (2) Each object of $\operatorname{Ext}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}\left(C,A\right)$ is refered as an extension from $A$ to $C$. (3) Every extension from $A$ to $C$ will be denoted with a capital letter $E$, or by $\overline{\eta}$, in case $\eta$ is a representative of the class $E$. (4) Given $\overline{\eta}\in\operatorname{Ext}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}\left(C,A\right)$ and $\overline{\eta^{\prime}}\in\operatorname{Ext}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}\left(C^{\prime% },A^{\prime}\right)$, we will call extension morphism from $\overline{\eta}$ to $\overline{\eta^{\prime}}$, to every short exact sequence morphism $\eta\rightarrow\eta^{\prime}$. (5) If $(\alpha,\beta,\gamma):E\rightarrow E^{\prime}$ and $(\alpha^{\prime},\beta^{\prime},\gamma^{\prime}):E^{\prime}\rightarrow E^{% \prime\prime}$ are extension morphisms, we define the composition morphism as $(\alpha^{\prime},\beta^{\prime},\gamma^{\prime})(\alpha,\beta,\gamma):=(\alpha% ^{\prime}\alpha,\beta^{\prime}\beta,\gamma^{\prime}\gamma)\mbox{.}$
Definition 2.19. Let $E\in\operatorname{Ext}_{\mathcal{C}}^{n}\left(C,A\right)$ and $E^{\prime}\in\operatorname{Ext}_{\mathcal{C}}^{m}\left(D,C\right)$. For $E=\overline{\eta}$ and $E^{\prime}=\overline{\eta^{\prime}}$, we define the composition extension $EE^{\prime}$ of $E$ with $E^{\prime}$, as $EE^{\prime}:=\overline{\eta\eta^{\prime}}$. If $\eta=\eta_{n}\cdots\eta_{1}$ is the natural decomposition of $\eta$, the induced extension factorization $E=\overline{\eta_{n}}\cdots\overline{\eta_{1}}$ is known as a natural decomposition of $E$.
Definition 2.3. [14, VII.1.] For $A,C\in\mathcal{C}$, let $\mathcal{E}_{\mathcal{C}}(K,N)$ denote the class of short exact sequences of the form $0\rightarrow N\overset{}{\rightarrow}M\overset{}{\rightarrow}K\rightarrow 0% \mbox{.}$
Definition 2.13. [14, VII.3.] We will make use of the following considerations. (1) For an exact sequence $\eta:\;0\rightarrow A\overset{}{\rightarrow}B_{n-1}\rightarrow\cdots% \rightarrow B_{0}\overset{}{\rightarrow}C\rightarrow 0$ in $\mathcal{C}$ we say that $\eta$ is an exact sequence of length $n$, and $A$ and $C$ are the left and right ends of $\eta$, respectively. (2) Let $\mathcal{E}_{\mathcal{C}}^{n}(L,N)$ denote the class of exact sequences of length $n$ with $L$ and $N$ as right and left ends. (3) Consider the following exact sequences in $\mathcal{C}$ $\displaystyle\eta:\;0\rightarrow N\overset{\mu}{\rightarrow}B_{n-1}\stackrel{{% \scriptstyle f_{n-1}}}{{\rightarrow}}\cdots\stackrel{{\scriptstyle f_{1}}}{{% \rightarrow}}B_{0}\overset{\pi}{\rightarrow}K\rightarrow 0$ , $\displaystyle\eta^{\prime}:\;0\rightarrow N^{\prime}\overset{\mu^{\prime}}{% \rightarrow}B^{\prime}_{n-1}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle f^{\prime}_{n-1}}}{{% \rightarrow}}\cdots\stackrel{{\scriptstyle f^{\prime}_{1}}}{{\rightarrow}}B^{% \prime}_{0}\overset{\pi^{\prime}}{\rightarrow}K^{\prime}\rightarrow 0$ . A morphism $\eta\rightarrow$$\eta^{\prime}$ is a collection of $n+2$ morphisms $(\alpha,\beta_{n-1},\cdots,\beta_{0},\gamma)$ in $\mathcal{C}$, where $\alpha:N\rightarrow N^{\prime}$, $\gamma:K\rightarrow K^{\prime}$, and $\beta_{i}:B_{i}\rightarrow B^{\prime}_{i}\>\forall i\in[0,n-1]$ are such that $\beta_{n-1}\mu=\mu^{\prime}\alpha\mbox{, }\gamma\pi=\pi^{\prime}\beta_{0}\mbox% { and }\beta_{i-1}f_{i}=f_{i}^{\prime}\beta_{i}\>\forall i\in[0,n-1]\mbox{.}$ Equivalently, we can say that a morphism of exact sequences of length $n$ is a commutative diagram $0$$N$$B_{n-1}$$\cdots$$B_{0}$$K$$0$$0$$N^{\prime}$$B^{\prime}_{n-1}$$\cdots$$B^{\prime}_{0}$$K^{\prime}$$0$
Definition 2.2. [14, VII.1.] Let $\alpha:N\rightarrow N^{\prime}$, $\beta:M\rightarrow M^{\prime}$, and $\gamma:K\rightarrow K^{\prime}$ be morphisms in $\mathcal{C}$, and $\eta:\;0\rightarrow N\overset{f}{\rightarrow}M\overset{g}{\rightarrow}K% \rightarrow 0\mbox{, }\eta^{\prime}:\;0\rightarrow N^{\prime}\overset{f^{% \prime}}{\rightarrow}M^{\prime}\overset{g^{\prime}}{\rightarrow}K^{\prime}\rightarrow 0$ be short exact sequences in $\mathcal{C}$. (1) We say that $(\alpha,\beta,\gamma):\eta\rightarrow\eta^{\prime}$ is a morphism of short exact sequences if $\beta f=f^{\prime}\alpha\;\mbox{and}\;\gamma g=g^{\prime}\beta\mbox{.}$ (2) We denote by $\eta\oplus\eta^{\prime}$ to the short exact sequence $0\rightarrow N\oplus N^{\prime}\overset{f\oplus f^{\prime}}{\rightarrow}M% \oplus M^{\prime}\overset{g\oplus g^{\prime}}{\rightarrow}K\oplus K^{\prime}% \rightarrow 0\mbox{.}$
Definition 2.9. [14, VII.1.] For $E\in\operatorname{Ext}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}\left(C,A\right)$, $\alpha:A\rightarrow A^{\prime}$ and $\gamma:C^{\prime}\rightarrow C$ in $\mathcal{C}$, we set $E\gamma:=\Phi_{\gamma}(E)$, and $\alpha E:=\Phi^{\alpha}(E)$.
Definition 3.1. [15, 1.4.] Let $\mathcal{C}$ and $I$ be categories, where $I$ is small (that is the class of objects of $I$ is a set). Let $F:I\rightarrow\mathcal{C}$ be a functor and $X\in\mathcal{C}$. A family of morphisms $\left\{\alpha_{i}:F(i)\rightarrow X\right\}_{i\in I}$ in $\mathcal{C}$ is co-compatible with $F$, if $\alpha_{i}=\alpha_{j}F(\lambda)$ for every $\lambda:i\rightarrow j$ in $I$. The colimit (or inductive limit) of $F$ is an object $\operatorname{colim}F\in\mathcal{C}$ with a co-compatible family of morphisms in $\mathcal{C}$ $\left\{\mu_{i}:F(i)\rightarrow\operatorname{colim}F\right\}_{i\in I}\mbox{,}$ such that for every co-compatible family of morphisms $\left\{\gamma_{i}:F(i)\rightarrow X\right\}_{i\in I}$, there is a unique morphism $\gamma:\operatorname{colim}F\rightarrow X$ such that $\gamma_{i}=\gamma\mu_{i}$ for every $i\in I$.
Definition 3.6. [15, 2.8.] An Ab3 category is an abelian category satisfying the following condition: (Ab3): For every set of objects $\left\{A_{i}\right\}_{i\in I}$ in $\mathcal{C}$ the coproduct $\bigoplus_{i\in I}A_{i}$ exists. We will refer to the dual condition as Ab3*.
Definition 2.16. [14, VII.3.] Consider the following exact sequences of length $n$ and $m$, respectively $\displaystyle\eta:\;0\rightarrow N\overset{\mu}{\rightarrow}B_{n}\rightarrow% \cdots\rightarrow B_{1}\overset{\pi}{\rightarrow}K\rightarrow 0$ , $\displaystyle\eta^{\prime}:\;0\rightarrow K\overset{\mu^{\prime}}{\rightarrow}% B^{\prime}_{m}\rightarrow\cdots\rightarrow B^{\prime}_{1}\overset{\pi^{\prime}% }{\rightarrow}L\rightarrow 0$ $\displaystyle.$ The composition sequence $\eta\eta^{\prime}$, of $\eta$ with $\eta^{\prime}$, is the exact sequence $0\rightarrow N\overset{\mu}{\rightarrow}B_{n}\rightarrow\cdots\rightarrow B_{1% }\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mu^{\prime}\pi}}{{\rightarrow}}B^{\prime}_{m}% \rightarrow\cdots\rightarrow B^{\prime}_{1}\overset{\pi^{\prime}}{\rightarrow}% L\rightarrow 0\mbox{.}$
Definition 2.4.1. Assume that $\underline{C}$ is endowed with a weight structure $w$. We will say that a (co)homological functor $H$ from $\underline{C}$ into an abelian category $\underline{A}$ is $w$-pure (or just pure if the choice of $w$ is clear) if $H$ kills both $\underline{C}_{w\geq 1}$ and $\underline{C}_{w\leq-1}$.
Definition 4.1.1. Let $\underline{H}$ be a full subcategory of a (triangulated) category $\underline{C}$. 1. We will say that the subcategory $\underline{H}$ is negative (in $\underline{C}$) if $\operatorname{Obj}\underline{H}\perp(\cup_{i>0}\operatorname{Obj}(\underline{H% }[i]))$.8In several papers (mostly, on representation theory and related matters) a negative subcategory satisfying certain additional assumptions was said to be silting. 2. Let $\underline{H}^{\prime}$ be the category of "formal coproducts" of objects of $\underline{H}$, i.e., the objects of $\underline{H}^{\prime}$ are of the form $\coprod_{i}P_{i}$ for (families of) $P_{i}\in\operatorname{Obj}\underline{H}$ and $\underline{H}^{\prime}(\coprod M_{i},\coprod N_{j})=\prod_{i}(\bigoplus_{j}% \underline{H}(M_{i},N_{j}))$. Then we will call $\operatorname{\operatorname{Kar}}(\underline{H}^{\prime})$ the formal coproductive hull of $\underline{H}$. 3. We will say that a full triangulated subcategory $\underline{D}\subset\underline{C}$ is localizing whenever $\underline{D}$ closed with respect to $\underline{C}$-coproducts. Respectively, we will call the smallest localizing subcategory of $\underline{C}$ that contains a given class $\mathcal{P}\subset\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$ the localizing subcategory of $\underline{C}$ generated by $\mathcal{P}$. 4. An object $M$ of $\underline{C}$ is said to be compact if the functor $H^{M}=\underline{C}(M,-):\underline{C}\to\operatorname{Ab}$ respects coproducts. 5. We will say that $\underline{C}$ is compactly generated by $\mathcal{P}\subset\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$ if $\mathcal{P}$ is a set of compact objects that generates it as its own localizing subcategory.
Definition 2.1.2. Let $m\leq n\in{\mathbb{Z}}$. 1. We will say that a morphism $g$ kills weights $m,\dots,n$ if it satisfies the equivalent conditions of the previous proposition (and we will say that $f$ kills weight $m$ if $n=m$); denote the class of all $\underline{C}$-morphisms killing weights $m,\dots,n$ by $\operatorname{Mor}_{\cancel{[m,n]}}\underline{C}$. 2. We will say that an object $M$ of $\underline{C}$ is without weights $m,\dots,n$ (or that $M$ avoids these weights) if $\operatorname{id}_{M}$ kills weights $m,\dots,n$; the class of $\underline{C}$-objects without weights $m,\dots,n$ will be denoted by $\underline{C}_{w\notin[m,n]}$.
Definition 3.1.1. 1. We will call a triangulated category $\underline{C}^{\prime}$ an idempotent extension of $\underline{C}$ if it contains $\underline{C}$ and there exists a fully faithful exact functor $\underline{C}^{\prime}\to\operatorname{\operatorname{Kar}}(\underline{C})$.5Recall that (according to Theorem 1.5 of [BaS01]) the category $\operatorname{\operatorname{Kar}}(\underline{C})$ can be naturally endowed with the structure of a triangulated category so that the natural embedding functor $\underline{C}\to\operatorname{\operatorname{Kar}}(\underline{C})$ is exact. Hence $\underline{C}^{\prime}$ is an idempotent extension of $\underline{C}$ if and only if any object of $\underline{C}^{\prime}$ is a retract of some object of $\underline{C}$. 2. We will say that a weight structure $w$ extends to an idempotent extension $\underline{C}^{\prime}$ of $\underline{C}$ whenever there exists a weight structure $w^{\prime}$ for $\underline{C}^{\prime}$ such that the embedding $\underline{C}\to\underline{C}^{\prime}$ is weight-exact. In this case we will call $w^{\prime}$ an extension of $w$. 3. We will call a weight-Karoubian category $(\underline{C}^{\prime},w^{\prime})$ (see Definition 1.2.2(4)) a weight-Karoubian extension of $(\underline{C},w)$ if $\underline{C}^{\prime}$ is an idempotent extension of $\underline{C}$ and $w^{\prime}$ is the extension of $w$ to it (cf. Proposition 3.1.2(1)).
Definition 1.2.1. I. A pair of subclasses $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0},\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}\subset\operatorname{Obj}% \underline{C}$ will be said to define a weight structure $w$ on a triangulated category $\underline{C}$ if they satisfy the following conditions. (i) $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}$ and $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}$ are retraction-closed in $\underline{C}$ (i.e., contain all $\underline{C}$-retracts of their objects). (ii) Semi-invariance with respect to translations. $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}\subset\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}[1]$, $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}[1]\subset\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}$. (iii) Orthogonality. $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}\perp\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}[1]$. (iv) Weight decompositions. For any $M\in\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$ there exists a distinguished triangle $LM\to M\to RM{\to}LM[1]$ such that $LM\in\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}$ and $RM\in\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}[1]$.
Definition 2.4.3. Assume that $\underline{C}$ is closed with respect to small coproducts. 1. We will say that $\underline{C}$ satisfies the Brown representability property if any cohomological functor from $\underline{C}$ into $\operatorname{Ab}$ that converts $\underline{C}$-coproducts into products of groups is representable in $\underline{C}$. 2. We will say that a weight structure $w$ on $\underline{C}$ is smashing if the class $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}$ is closed with respect to (small) $\underline{C}$-coproducts (cf. Proposition 1.2.4(3)).
Definition 1.2.2. Let $i,j\in{\mathbb{Z}}$; assume that a triangulated category $\underline{C}$ is endowed with a weight structure $w$. 1. The full category ${\underline{Hw}}\subset\underline{C}$ whose objects are $\underline{C}_{w=0}=\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}\cap\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}$ is called the heart of $w$. 2. $\underline{C}_{w\geq i}$ (resp. $\underline{C}_{w\leq i}$, resp. $\underline{C}_{w=i}$) will denote the class $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}[i]$ (resp. $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}[i]$, resp. $\underline{C}_{w=0}[i]$). 3. $\underline{C}_{[i,j]}$ denotes $\underline{C}_{w\geq i}\cap\underline{C}_{w\leq j}$; so, this class equals $\{0\}$ if $i>j$. 4. We will say that $\underline{C}$ is weight-Karoubian if ${\underline{Hw}}$ is Karoubian. 5. Let $\underline{C}^{\prime}$ be a triangulated category endowed with a weight structure $w^{\prime}$; let $F:\underline{C}\to\underline{C}^{\prime}$ be an exact functor. Then $F$ is said to be weight-exact (with respect to $w,w^{\prime}$) if it maps $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}$ into $\underline{C}^{\prime}_{w^{\prime}\leq 0}$ and sends $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}$ into $\underline{C}^{\prime}_{w^{\prime}\geq 0}$. 6. Let $\underline{D}$ be a full triangulated subcategory of $\underline{C}$. We will say that $w$ restricts to $\underline{D}$ whenever the couple $(\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}\cap\operatorname{Obj}\underline{D},\ \underline{C}_{w% \geq 0}\cap\operatorname{Obj}\underline{D})$ is a weight structure on $\underline{D}$. 7. We will say that $M$ is left (resp., right) $w$-degenerate (or weight-degenerate if the choice of $w$ is clear) if $M$ belongs to $\cap_{i\in{\mathbb{Z}}}\underline{C}_{w\geq i}$ (resp. to $\cap_{i\in{\mathbb{Z}}}\underline{C}_{w\leq i}$). 8. We will say that $w$ is left (resp., right) non-degenerate if all left (resp. right) weight-degenerate objects are zero. 9. We will call $\cup_{i\in{\mathbb{Z}}}\underline{C}_{w\geq i}$ (resp. $\cup_{i\in{\mathbb{Z}}}\underline{C}_{w\leq i}$) the class of $w$-bounded below (resp., $w$-bounded above) objects of $\underline{C}$.
Definition 1.3.1. Let $A$ and $B$ be objects of $B\in\operatorname{Obj}K(\underline{B})$, and $m_{1},m_{2}\in C({\underline{Hw}})(A,B)$/ 1. We will write $m_{1}\backsim m_{2}$ if $m_{1}-m_{2}=d_{B}h+jd_{A}$ for some collections of arrows $j^{*},h^{*}:A^{*}\to B^{*-1}$. We will call this relation the weak homotopy one (cf. Remark 1.3.3(4 below). 2. More generally, assume that $k\leq l\in(\{-\infty\}\cup{\mathbb{Z}}\cup\{+\infty\})$. Then we will write $m_{1}\backsim_{[k,l]}m_{2}$ if $m_{1}-m_{2}$ is weakly homotopic to certain $m_{0}$ such that $m_{0}^{i}=0$ for $k\leq i\leq l$ (and $i\in{\mathbb{Z}}$).
Definition 3.1.5. For an object $M$ of $\underline{C}$ (where $\underline{C}$ is endowed with a weight structure $w$) we will say that $M$ is essentially $w$-positive (resp. essentially $w$-negative) if it is a retract of some $M^{\prime}\in\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$ such that $M^{\prime}$ is an extension of an element of $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}$ by a right $w$-degenerate object of $\underline{C}$ (resp. $M^{\prime}$ is an extension of a left $w$-degenerate object of $\underline{C}$ by an element of $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}$).
Definition 2.3.3. We will say that $M\in\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$ is $w$-degenerate (or weight-degenerate) if $t(M)$ is zero (in $K_{\mathfrak{w}}({\underline{Hw}})$ and so also in $K({\underline{Hw}})$).
Definition 2.1. A linear category of partitions $\mathscr{K}$ is called easy if, for every $k,l\in\mathbb{N}_{0}$, there is a set $\mathscr{C}(k,l)\subseteq\mathscr{P}(k,l)$ such that $\mathscr{K}(k,l)=\operatorname{span}\mathscr{C}(k,l)$. Otherwise it is called non-easy.
Definition 18. Let $(S,<)$ be a well ordered set. Define $\mathfrak{O}_{S}:S^{\otimes}\to S^{\otimes}$ as the function such that: • $\mathfrak{O}_{S}(s)$ is a permutation of $s$; • Elements of $\mathfrak{O}_{S}(s)$ are monotonically increasing: If $\mathfrak{O}_{S}(s)=(s_{0},\dots,s_{n})$, then $s_{i}\leq s_{i+1}$ for each $0\leq i<n$. Abusing notation, we can define $\mathfrak{O}_{S}:S^{\oplus}\to S^{\otimes}$ as the function mapping each multiset $s$ to the unique string $\mathfrak{O}_{S}(s)$ such that $\mathfrak{M}_{S}(\mathfrak{O}_{S}(s))=s$ and $\mathfrak{O}_{S}(\mathfrak{O}_{S}(s))=\mathfrak{O}_{S}(s)$.
Definition 11. Given a Petri net $N$, we map it to the FSSMC $\mathcal{F}N$ generated as in Definition 8, with $P_{N}$ as the set of object generators and generating morphisms given by $T:=\left\{(t,\mathfrak{O}_{N}({{}^{\circ}}(t)_{N}),\mathfrak{O}_{N}({(t)_{N}^{% \circ}}))\>\middle|\>t\in T_{N}\right\}$
Definition 4. Given a set $S$, we define the multiplicity of $S$ as the homomorphism $\mathfrak{M}_{S}:S^{\otimes}\to S^{\oplus}$ sending a string $s$ to the multiset associating to each element of $S$ its number of occurrencies in $s$. When no ambiguity arises, we will use $\mathfrak{M}$ in place of $\mathfrak{M}_{S}$.
Definition 8. A free strict SMC (FSSMC) is a symmetric monoidal category whose monoid of objects is $S^{\otimes}$ for some set of generators $S$, and whose morphisms are generated by the following introduction rules: $\displaystyle\frac{s\in S^{\otimes}}{id_{s}:s\to s}\qquad\frac{s,t\in S^{% \otimes}}{\sigma_{s,t}:{s\otimes t}\to{s\otimes t}}\qquad\frac{(\alpha,s,t)\in T% }{\alpha:s\to t}$ $\displaystyle\frac{\alpha:A\to B,\,\,\alpha^{\prime}:A^{\prime}\to B^{\prime}}% {\alpha\otimes\alpha^{\prime}:{A\otimes A^{\prime}}\to{B\otimes B^{\prime}}}% \qquad\frac{\alpha:A\to B,\,\,\beta:B\to C}{\alpha;\beta:A\to C}$ Where elements of the set $T$ are triples $(\alpha,s,t)$ with $s,t\in S^{\otimes}$. Morphisms are quotiented by the following equations, for $\alpha:A\to B$, $\alpha^{\prime}:A^{\prime}\to B^{\prime}$, $\alpha^{\prime\prime}:A^{\prime\prime}\to B^{\prime\prime}$, $\beta:B\to C$, $\beta^{\prime}:B^{\prime}\to C^{\prime}$, $\gamma:C\to D$: $\displaystyle\alpha;id_{B}=$ $\displaystyle\,\,\alpha=id_{A};\alpha$ $\displaystyle\quad(\alpha;\beta);\gamma$ $\displaystyle=\alpha;(\beta;\gamma)$ $\displaystyle\epsilon\otimes\alpha=$ $\displaystyle\,\,\alpha=\alpha\otimes\epsilon$ $\displaystyle\quad(\alpha\otimes\alpha^{\prime})\otimes\alpha^{\prime\prime}$ $\displaystyle=\alpha\otimes(\alpha^{\prime}\otimes\alpha^{\prime\prime})$ $\displaystyle id_{A}\otimes id_{A^{\prime}}$ $\displaystyle=id_{A\otimes A^{\prime}}$ $\displaystyle\quad(\alpha\otimes\alpha^{\prime});(\beta\otimes\beta^{\prime})$ $\displaystyle=(\alpha;\beta)\otimes(\alpha^{\prime};\beta^{\prime})$ $\displaystyle\sigma_{A,A^{\prime}\otimes A^{\prime\prime}}=(\sigma_{A,A^{% \prime}}$ $\displaystyle\otimes id_{A^{\prime\prime}});(id_{A}\otimes\sigma_{A^{\prime},A% ^{\prime\prime}})$ $\displaystyle\quad\sigma_{A,A^{\prime}};\sigma_{A^{\prime},A}$ $\displaystyle=id_{A\otimes A^{\prime}}$ $\displaystyle\quad\qquad\mathrlap{\sigma_{A,A^{\prime}};(\alpha^{\prime}% \otimes\alpha)=(\alpha\otimes\alpha^{\prime});\sigma_{B,B^{\prime}}}$
Definition 15. Let $S$ be a set. Given a string $s\in S^{\otimes}$, denote with $s^{l}$ the string obtained as follows: • Starting from the left, consider the $i$-th entry of $s$, call it $s_{i}$. It will be equal to some generator $t$. • If, for all $j<i$, it is $s_{i}\neq s_{j}$, then set $s_{i}$ equal to the formal writing $t^{0}$; • Otherwise, there are others entries $j$ with $j<i$ and both $s_{i}=t=s_{j}$. Consider the biggest of such $j$. If $t$ has been replaced with the formal writing $t^{k}$ at entry $j$, replace it with the formal writing $t^{k+1}$ at entry $i$.
Definition 23. To an ordered FSSMC $(\mathcal{C},<_{\mathcal{C}})$ we associate the net $(\mathcal{N}\mathcal{C},<_{\mathcal{N}\mathcal{C}})$, where the order relations $<_{\mathcal{C}}$ and $<_{\mathcal{N}\mathcal{C}}$ are the same.
Definition 2. Let $S$ be a set. We denote with $S^{\oplus}$ and $S^{\otimes}$ the set of finite multisets and the set of strings of finite length over $S$, respectively. The length of a string $s$ is denoted with $|s|$, while the empty string with $\epsilon$.
Definition 17. A symmetry $\sigma:s\to s^{\prime}$ is called swap-free if, for any decomposition of $\sigma$ into basic blocks $\sigma=\sigma_{1};\dots;\sigma_{n}$ and fixed labelings of generators $t^{j},t^{k}$, there is a bijective correspondence between the sets: $\left\{i\>\middle|\>\sigma_{i}^{l}:=id_{u}\otimes\sigma_{t^{j},t^{k}}\otimes id% _{t}\right\}\simeq\left\{i\>\middle|\>\sigma_{i}^{l}:=id_{u^{\prime}}\otimes% \sigma_{t^{k},t^{j}}\otimes id_{t^{\prime}}\right\}$
Definition 1 (List of requirements). 1. We want to map each net to a free strict symmetric monoidal category, representing its possible executions. Free structures are particularly appealing for us since they are easier to handle computationally. Moreover we do not want to change the net/FSSMC definition too much to find a correspondence between the two, because we want to leverage on the diagrammatic formalism developed for both, see Requirement 4. 2. We want the mapping from nets to FFSMCs to be computationally feasible. 3. We want the FSSMCs corresponding to nets to represent computations in a meaningful way. In particular, we want to be able to map net computations to other categories, translating the generating morphisms of a FSSMC into real operations (which can be pure functions, asynchronous calls etc.) via functors. Therefore, FSSMCs should not identify computations which are conceptually distinct. Moreover, any morphism in the FSSMC must correspond to a possible computation of the net. 4. We want our mapping to be useful for intuition: Users should be able to program in a goal-oriented way using nets (as explained in Genovese), test against their properties with already developed tools (e.g. Sobocinski2013a), and then map the net to its computations to establish links with a semantics. 5. We want users to be able to morph a net into another. Such morphisms should automatically be lifted to morphisms of net executions. We moreover want users to be able to “tweak” morphisms between executions directly in case the lifting provided is not satisfying for the task at hand.
Definition 20. A morphism of ordered Petri nets $f:(N,<_{N})\to(M,<_{M})$ is just a morphism $N\to M$ between their underlying nets.
Definition 13. Let $\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D}$ be FSSMCs. A strict monoidal functor $F:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ is called transition-preserving if it maps generating morphisms in $\mathcal{C}$ to morphisms in $\mathcal{D}$ of the form $\sigma;t;\sigma^{\prime}$, where $t$ is a generating morphism and $\sigma,\sigma^{\prime}$ are symmetries.
Definition 6. A morphism of Petri nets $f:N\to M$ is specified by a couple $({f}_{Pl},{f}_{Tr})$, with ${f}_{Pl}:P_{N}^{\oplus}\to P_{M}^{\oplus}$ multiset homomorphism and ${f}_{Tr}:T_{N}\to T_{M}$ function such that ${{}^{\circ}}(-)_{N};{f}_{Pl}={f}_{Tr};{{}^{\circ}}(-)_{M}\qquad{(-)_{N}^{\circ% }};{f}_{Pl}={f}_{Tr};{(-)_{M}^{\circ}}$
Definition 12. To every FSSMC $\mathcal{C}$, we associate the net $\mathcal{N}\mathcal{C}$ defined as follows: • Places of $\mathcal{N}\mathcal{C}$ are the generating objects of $\mathcal{C}$; • Transitions of $\mathcal{N}\mathcal{C}$ are the generating morphisms of $\mathcal{C}$; • ${{}^{\circ}}(t)_{\mathcal{N}\mathcal{C}}$, for $t:A\to B$ primitive morphism of $\mathcal{C}$, is defined as $\mathfrak{M}(A)$; • ${(t)_{\mathcal{N}\mathcal{C}}^{\circ}}$, for $t:A\to B$ primitive morphism of $\mathcal{C}$, is defined as $\mathfrak{M}(B)$.
Definition 19. A ordered Petri net is a couple $(N,<_{N})$ where $N$ is a Petri net and $<_{N}$ is a well ordering on $P_{N}$.
Definition 9. Given a set $S$ we denote with $\operatorname{Sym}_{S}$ the category generated as in Definition 8, where the monoid of objects is $S^{\otimes}$ and the set of generating morphisms $T$ is empty.
Definition 22. Given an ordered Petri net $(N,<_{N})$, we map it to the ordered, free on objects strict symmetric monoidal category $(\mathcal{F}N,<_{\mathcal{F}N})$, where the order relations $<_{N}$ and $<_{\mathcal{F}N}$ are the same.
Definition 16. Let $\sigma_{1};\dots;\sigma_{n}:s\to s^{\prime}$ be a composition of basic blocks in $\operatorname{Sym}_{S}$. Denote with $\sigma_{1}^{l};\dots;\sigma_{n}^{l}$ the symmetry obtained by using the following procedure: • Suppose $\sigma_{1}:=id_{u}\otimes\sigma_{s_{1},s_{2}}\otimes id_{t}$. Define $\sigma_{1}^{l}$ by replacing $s_{1},s_{2}$ and every generating object in $u,t$ with their labelled writings so that the source of $\sigma_{1}^{l}$ is $s^{l}$; • Apply the previous point to $\sigma_{i+1}$ such that the source of $\sigma_{i+1}^{l}$ coincides with the target of $\sigma_{i}^{l}$; • Repeat the step for every $i$.
Definition 7. A free-on-objects, strict SMC (symmetric monoidal category) is a strict symmetric monoidal category whose monoid of objects is freely generated.
Definition 21. An ordered FSSMC is a couple $(\mathcal{C},<_{\mathcal{C}})$ where $\mathcal{C}$ is a FSSMC and $<_{\mathcal{C}}$ is a well order on its set of object generators. Ordered FSSMCs and transition-preserving functors between them form a category, denoted $\textbf{FSSMC}_{<}$.
Definition 14. A morphism in $\operatorname{Sym}_{S}$ is called a basic block if it is of the form $id_{u}\otimes\sigma_{s_{1},s_{2}}\otimes id_{t}$ for some objects $u,t$ and some object generators $s_{1},s_{2}$.
Definition 5. A Petri net $N$ is a tuple $(P_{N},T_{N},{{}^{\circ}}(-)_{N},{(-)_{N}^{\circ}})$, where $P_{N}$ and $T_{N}$ are sets, called the set of places and transitions of $N$, respectively, while ${{}^{\circ}}(-)_{N}$ and ${(-)_{N}^{\circ}}$ are functions $T_{N}\to P_{N}^{\oplus}$, representing the input/output places, respectively, connected to each transition.
Definition 3. A multiset homomorphism $X:A^{\oplus}\to B^{\oplus}$ (respectively, monoid homomorphism $Y:A^{\otimes}\to B^{\otimes}$) is called grounded if there is a function $f:A\to B$ such that ${f}^{\oplus}=X$ (respectively $f^{\otimes}=Y$).
Definition 10 (From Sassone1995, Def. 3.5). Given a Petri net $(N)$, we map it to the free-on-objects, strict symmetric monoidal category $\mathcal{Q}N$ defined as follows: • The monoid of objects of $\mathcal{Q}N$ is freely generated by $P_{N}$; • Morphisms are generated by the following introduction rules: $\displaystyle\frac{s\in P_{N}^{\otimes}}{id_{s}:s\to s}\quad\frac{s,t\in P_{N}% ^{\otimes}}{\sigma_{s,t}:{s\otimes t}\to{t\otimes s}}$ $\displaystyle\frac{t\in T_{N}}{t_{u,v}:u\to v}\quad\forall u,v.(\mathfrak{M}(u% )={{}^{\circ}}(t)_{N}\wedge\mathfrak{M}(v)={(t)_{N}^{\circ}})$ $\displaystyle\frac{\alpha:A\to B,\,\,\alpha^{\prime}:A^{\prime}\to B^{\prime}}% {\alpha\otimes\alpha^{\prime}:{A\otimes A^{\prime}}\to{B\otimes B^{\prime}}}% \qquad\frac{\alpha:A\to C,\,\,\beta:B\to C}{\alpha;\beta:A\to C}$ • Morphisms are quotiented by the same axioms of Definition 8 plus the following one, for $p:u\to u^{\prime}$, $q:v\to v^{\prime}$ symmetries: $p;t_{u^{\prime},v^{\prime}}=t_{u,v};q$
Definition 1.1. [KZ, Definition 3.1] Let $\mathscr{C}$ be a triangulated category with a shift functor $[1]$. (1) A subcategory $\mathscr{X}$ of $\mathscr{C}$ is called rigid if ${\rm Hom}_{\mathscr{C}}(\mathscr{X},\mathscr{X}[1])=0$. (2) A functorially finite subcategory $\mathscr{X}$ of $\mathscr{C}$ is called cluster tilting if $\mathscr{X}=\{M\in\mathscr{C}\ |\ {\rm Hom}_{\mathscr{C}}(\mathscr{X},M[1])=0% \}=\{M\in\mathscr{C}\ |\ {\rm Hom}_{\mathscr{C}}(M,\mathscr{X}[1])=0\}.$
Definition 2.1. [Ha, Definition 4.1] Let $\mathscr{C}$ be a triangulated category. A triangle $A\xrightarrow{~{}u~{}}B\xrightarrow{~{}v~{}}C\xrightarrow{~{}w~{}}A[1]$ in $\mathscr{C}$ is called an Auslander-Reiten triangle if • $A,B$ are indecomposable; • $w\neq 0$ • If $f\colon X\to C$ is not a split epimorphism, then there exists a morphism $f^{\prime}\colon X\to B$ such that $f^{\prime}v=f$. In this case, we call $u$ is a source morphism and $v$ is a sink morphism. The notions of a source morphism and a sink morphism are also known as minimal left almost split morphism and minimal right split morphism, respectively.
Definition 4.11. $\mathcal{V}$ admits left uniform Maehara interpolation if for any finite sets $\overline{y},\overline{z}$ and finite sets of equations $\Sigma(\overline{y},\overline{z}),\Delta(\overline{y},\overline{z})$, there exists a finite set of equations $\Pi(\overline{y})$ such that for any finite set of equations $\Gamma(\overline{x},\overline{y})$, $\Gamma,\Sigma\models_{\mathcal{V}}\Delta\iff\Gamma\models_{\mathcal{V}}\Pi.$
Definition 2.13. $\mathcal{V}$ admits Maehara interpolation if for any finite sets $\overline{x},\overline{y},\overline{z}$ and finite sets of equations $\Gamma(\overline{x},\overline{y}),\Sigma(\overline{y},\overline{z}),\Delta(% \overline{y},\overline{z})$ satisfying $\Gamma,\Sigma\models_{\mathcal{V}}\Delta$, there exists a set of equations $\Pi(\overline{y})$ such that $\Gamma\models_{\mathcal{V}}\Pi$ and $\Pi,\Sigma\models_{\mathcal{V}}\Delta$.
Definition 3.12. $\mathcal{V}$ admits right uniform Maehara interpolation if for any finite sets $\overline{x},\overline{y}$ and a finite set of equations $\Gamma(\overline{x},\overline{y})$, there exists a finite set of equations $\Pi(\overline{y})$ such that for any finite sets of equations $\Sigma(\overline{y},\overline{z}),\Delta(\overline{y},\overline{z})$, $\Gamma,\Sigma\models_{\mathcal{V}}\Delta\iff\Pi,\Sigma\models_{\mathcal{V}}\Delta.$
Definition 2.1. Let $h\colon{\bf{A}}\to{\bf{B}}$ be a homomorphism. The adjoint lifting of $h$ to the congruence lattices of ${\bf{A}}$ and ${\bf{B}}$ is the pair of maps $h^{*}\colon\operatorname{\mathrm{Con}}{\bf{A}}\leftrightarrows\operatorname{% \mathrm{Con}}{\bf{B}}\nobreak\mskip 6.0mu plus 1.0mu \mathpunct{}\nonscript% \mskip-3.0mu {:}\mskip 2.0mu h^{-1}$, $\displaystyle h^{*}(\psi)$ $\displaystyle:={\rm Cg}_{{}_{{\bf{B}}}}\{(h(a),h(a^{\prime})):(a,a^{\prime})% \in\psi\},$ $\displaystyle h^{-1}(\theta)$ $\displaystyle:=\{(a,a^{\prime})\in A^{2}:(h(a),h(a^{\prime}))\in\theta\}=\ker h% (-)/{\theta}.$ We call $h^{*}$ the direct image lifting and $h^{-1}$ the inverse image lifting of $h$. We denote the composite map $h^{-1}\circ h^{*}$ by $c_{h}\colon\operatorname{\mathrm{Con}}{\bf{A}}\to\operatorname{\mathrm{Con}}{% \bf{A}}$.
Definition 2.9. $\mathcal{V}$ admits deductive interpolation if for any finite sets $\overline{x},\overline{y},\overline{z}$ and finite set of equations $\Sigma(\overline{x},\overline{y})\cup\{\varepsilon(\overline{y},\overline{z})\}$ satisfying $\Sigma\models_{\mathcal{V}}\varepsilon$, there exists a finite set of equations $\Pi(\overline{y})$ such that $\Sigma\models_{\mathcal{V}}\Pi$ and $\Pi\models_{\mathcal{V}}\varepsilon$.
